article.description:
Sheryl Swoopes can only hope the WNBA
All-Stars are given more freedom to play exciting basketball next
week than the Comets and the Monarchs got Friday night.
article.headline: Both teams complain of lack of any continuity
article.linkText: Tightly called game leaves Comets frustrated, but still winners
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes can only hope the WNBA
All-Stars are given more freedom to play exciting basketball next
week than the Comets and the Monarchs got Friday night.

	   Swoopes had 15 points and five assists as Houston won for the
11th time in 12 games, beating last-place Sacramento 74-60 in a
game featuring 44 baskets, 43 fouls and plenty of frustration for
both winners and losers.

	   Any one of the 5,000 Ruthie Bolton bobblehead dolls handed out
in Arco Arena had almost as much freedom to roam as the players,
who trudged through the odd spectacle of a stifling second half in
which fouls were called on nearly every collision.

	   ''They were kind of taking the fun out of the game, and taking
the fans out of the game,'' said Swoopes, the leading vote-getter
for the All-Star Game next week in Washington. ''I mean, this is
professional basketball. At some point, you've got to let some
things go.''

	   Tina Thompson had 12 points and seven rebounds for the Comets,
who got their league-leading 16th victory and maintained their
virtual tie with Los Angeles atop the Western Conference heading
into the All-Star break.

	   ''You could see it on the faces of the players and the
coaches,'' Thompson said. ''We've been around this game and playing
it most of our lives, so to not be able to play the game we love is
frustrating.''

	   Tiffani Johnson scored 13 points, and Janeth Arcain had 12 in a
balanced attack for Houston (16-4), which held the Monarchs to one
field goal over a 9:52 span in the second half. The Comets scored
just 12 points during the span, but under the circumstances, it was
enough to pull away.

	   The second half was ugly both on the court and in the stands.
Approximately half of the game's fouls were called by referee Kurt
Walker, who was hit by a small unidentified object thrown from the
angry crowd with nine minutes left. The fans were warned during a
break in action.

	   ''I don't know if I've ever seen that kind of (refereeing) in
this league before,'' Sacramento coach Maura McHugh said. ''The
whistle blew, and everybody was looking around wondering what
happened, and it was on both sides. It broke up our whole momentum
in the second half.''

	   Tangela Smith led Sacramento (3-15) with 15 points. Yolanda
Griffith scored seven points on 1-for-6 shooting in her second game
back from an injury for the Monarchs, who snapped their eight-game
losing streak with a victory over Cleveland on Thursday.

	   ''We couldn't establish an inside game or an outside game,''
Griffith said. ''We would make a pass, and then just stand there.
We need to stay involved.''

	   All-Star Ticha Penicheiro, also playing her second game back
from injury, had 11 points and nine assists, but Sacramento shot
less than 35 percent and was unable to win consecutive games for
the first time in its star-crossed season. Bolton added 10 points
and five rebounds.

	   Houston's franchise-record 10-game winning streak was snapped in
Phoenix on Thursday night, but the Comets rebounded behind another
stellar all-around game from Swoopes.

	   ''We didn't want to lose any games before the break, but we knew
that with Ticha and Yo coming back, they're a better team,'' said
Swoopes, who also had four assists.

	   The Comets took the lead for good midway through the first half,
but they couldn't pull away from the Monarchs until the final
minutes. Thompson went scoreless in the second half, but Arcain had
eight points and three of her six assists.
